---
<SiteLayout site="migratingmammals" title="Guide to Phone Plans Abroad: eSIMs & Keeping Your Number" description="Learn how to use eSIMs, buy local SIM cards, and affordably keep your home country phone number when moving abroad." canonical="https://migratingmammals.com/guide-phone-plan-abroad" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Guide to Phone Plans Abroad</h1>
      <p>eSIMs, local SIMs, and keeping your home number.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="content-section">
      <p>Staying connected the moment you land is essential for navigating to your accommodation and contacting loved ones. This guide covers the cheapest ways to get data abroad and the tricks to keeping your home country phone number.</p>

      <h2>Travel eSIMs (Airalo, Holafly)</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>If you have a modern smartphone, the easiest way to get data is via an eSIM.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Buy Before You Fly:</strong> You can download an eSIM profile using apps like Airalo or Nomad while still at home on Wi-Fi. It will activate the moment your plane lands.</li>
          <li><strong>Data Only:</strong> Most travel eSIMs provide data only, not a local phone number. They are perfect for using WhatsApp, Google Maps, and Uber during your first week.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Getting a Local SIM Card</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>Once you settle in, you should transition to a local phone plan. Travel eSIMs are too expensive for long-term use, and you will eventually need a local phone number to register for a bank account or sign a lease.</p>
        <p><strong>Important:</strong> Ensure your phone is "unlocked" from your home carrier before you leave, otherwise it will reject foreign SIM cards.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Keeping Your Home Number (For SMS Codes)</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>Don't just cancel your home phone plan! You will still need your old number to receive two-factor authentication (2FA) text messages from your home country banks.</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Port to Google Voice:</strong> (US only). For a one-time $20 fee, you can port your number to Google Voice. You will then receive all calls and texts over Wi-Fi or local data for free.</li>
          <li><strong>Cheap Pre-Paid Plans:</strong> Port your number to the cheapest possible pre-paid plan (e.g., Ultra Mobile PayGo at $3/month) and turn on Wi-Fi Calling. As long as you are connected to Wi-Fi, you can receive SMS codes globally for free.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h2>Cross-Links and Related Information</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <p>Unlocking your phone and setting up an eSIM are crucial tasks for Phase 3 of your <a href="/moving-abroad-checklist">Moving Abroad Checklist</a>.</p>
        <p>Having a functioning phone is the foundation of your <a href="/first-month-abroad-guide">First Month Abroad</a>, allowing you to easily set up your <a href="/guide-international-banking">International Banking</a>.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>What is an eSIM?</h3>
        <p>An eSIM is a digital SIM card that allows you to activate a cellular plan without having to use a physical nano-SIM. You can buy them through apps like Airalo or Holafly before you travel.</p>

        <h3>How can I keep my home phone number?</h3>
        <p>You can port your home phone number to a Voice over IP (VoIP) service like Google Voice, Skype, or a cheap pre-paid plan with Wi-Fi calling. This allows you to receive bank SMS codes without paying high international roaming fees.</p>

        <h3>Should I get a local SIM card?</h3>
        <p>Yes. While travel eSIMs are great for your first week, a local plan is almost always cheaper for long-term data and gives you a local phone number, which is necessary for food delivery, banking, and government registration.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
